				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The purpose of the ad is to set the Church of Christ apart from the rest of the chuches.   Otherwise, the ad would have no purpose.  To set itself apart from other churches, the Church of Christ is portraying them as exclusionary of gays while they are not.  But the fact is is that the rest of the churches do not exclude gays.  Therefore, the ad portrays other churches in a false light.
<br />

<br />
Look at the language and the metaphors emplyed by the ad.  First, there is the velvet rope, the quintessential metaphor of exclusive -- and excluding -- clubs.  Then you have the black clad "bouncers" pushing away purportedly gay people with hostile language: "No way." "Not you," "Go away."  The implication is that churches other than the Church of Christ actively and aggressively exclude people, particularly gays.
<br />

<br />
Look.  The election is over.  Bush is against gay marriage, but he is in favor of civil unions.  CBS's choice to not air the ad is simply a liberal protest over a mispercieved administration policy, just like the liberal airwaves' choice not to air Saving Privite Ryan was a protest over the FCC's recent crack-down on Stern's potty mouth and Jackson's tit.
<br />

<br />
In other words, the CBS protest is evidence of a liberal bias, not a conservative one.  But a lot of you are sucking up this fiegned ploy like a Hoover Deluxe.<br />_________________<br />Old Bard of Brell
<br />
Proud Member of Poison Arrow</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
