				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Rodric: The same can be said of the WSJ, and the WSJ is even more insidious because they've been often known to take false stories from less credible conservative papers (American Spectator, Washington Times) and run them, prompting other mainstream media outlets to run the story as well.
<br />

<br />
Chants: You're speaking tautologies if you're trying to say the ad was the church trying to distinguish itself from more exclusionary churches. Where you are simply wrong is when you try to add the words "all" or "the majority"to the equation - there's nothing that implies the UCC is the only church, or one of only a handful, that is inclusive. However, if you want to get your moral indignation going, the UCC did make the argument that exclusionary churches are straying from Christ's message.
<br />

<br />
Also, Bush waffled on the issue of civil unions, and people with his campaign certainly supported anti-civil union referendums on ballots last month. Plus I thought the FMA text that Bush supported made civil unions against the law too, but I could be wrong about that.
<br />

<br />
Oh, and to turn this around and say CBS and NBC have a liberal bias for refusing to air this ad... come on, man. Who are you kidding?</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
