			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I agree with you 100% that Bushed waffled on the issue of civil unions and gay marriage.  There is no substantive difference between the two, and to promote one without the other is political waffling, QED.
<br />

<br />
On another note, I never said NBC's refusal to air the ad exposed thier liberal bias.  I only siad it exposed CBS's bias.
<br />

<br />
This is the CBS position, according to the UCC:
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">  "Because this commercial touches on the exclusion of gay couples...and the fact that the executive branch has recently proposed a Constitutional amendment to define marriage as a union between a man and a woman, this spot is unacceptable for broadcast," the church quoted CBS as saying. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Here is the NBC position according to NBC:
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">An NBC spokeswoman said the problem with the ad was not its depiction of same sex couples at church, but its implication that other religions are not open to all people. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
The NBC position and interpretation of the ad coincides with my own.
<br />

<br />
Assuming that the UCC is accurately quoting CBS and its position -- I think it is -- then this is a political jab to the administration from CBS.  Basically, CBS is saying that the Bush administration is just too big and bad to for this small fish network to air ads contrary to its party line.  Yeah, right.
<br />

<br />
On another note, brand loyalty is not the same thing as loyalty to one's faith.  So all this advertizing  talk equating Coke or Pepsi or hamburgers to a religion is just plain nonsense.  If anyone (Relbeek, Partha) thinks that a network should exercise the same judgment in choosing to air product ads versus religious ads is completely tone deaf to basic marketing principles.  
<br />

<br />
Although brand loyalty is important, such loyalty simply does not carry the same emotional attachment one has to a religion.  Therefore, if an ad promoting a religion is disrespectful of other religions -- as this ad was by implication -- then the backlash will be more powerful than it would be if it featured an ad disrespecfult of a product.  I simply never hear of, say, a Ford Truck enthusiast boycotting a network because it featured a Chevy truck ad.  I can easily see a boycott stemming from one who feels thier religion was impugned.
<br />

<br />
I read the Journal every day.  On Monday, it featured an editorial critical of Republicans.  Specifically, it took them to task for becoming entrenched, being fiscally irresponsible, and for straying away from thier core principles.
<br />

<br />
I do not want to pick at nits, but I disagree with the circulation data cited above.  According to the recent data collected by an advertizing auditing firm, USA Today has the highest circulation, followed by the WSJ, then the NYT.  If I recall correctly, the USA Today is at 2.2 million; WSJ is at 2.1, and the Times is at 1.6.  Anyway, here is the link.
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www.accessabc.com/reader/top100.htm" target="_blank">http://www.accessabc.com/reader/top100.htm</a>
<br />

<br />
It is interesting that the Wash. Post has a lower circulation than the LA Times; but I don't think that the LA Times has anywhere near the influence of the Wash. Post.  The point is, sure, circulation matters.  But it is not determinative.
<br />

<br />
The NYT editorial page is more influential than the WJS editorial page.  I wish that it were not true.  But it is.  The Times has pentrated the American psyche like no other paper.  People love it, hate it, few are neutral.  People love it because it is well written, articulate, they agree with it, and they know it is influential.  People hate it because it is well written, articulate, they disagree with it, and they know it is very influential.
<br />

<br />
To demonstrate just how deeply entrenched the Times is in the American psyche, there is a quiz out there which compares the taker to a variety of thier many well-known editorial page writers.
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://quizilla.com/users/drakespeare/quizzes/Which%20New%20York%20%20Times%20Op-Ed%20Columnist%20Are%20You?/" target="_blank">http://quizilla.com/users/drakespeare/quizzes/Which%20New%20York%20%20Times%20Op-Ed%20Columnist%20Are%20You?/</a>
<br />

<br />
The WJS has no such test.  People simply do not recognize thier writers on the level that people recognize the Time's writers to justify such a test.  That's probably because the Times is far more widely quoted, followed, read, and exposed.<br />_________________<br />Old Bard of Brell
<br />
Proud Member of Poison Arrow</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
