				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Although the FCC reglates the netowrks, it does not micromanage a stations advertizing decisions.  Here is the FCC's position on a station's advertizing:
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www.fcc.gov/mb/audio/decdoc/public_and_broadcasting.html#ADS" target="_blank">http://www.fcc.gov/mb/audio/decdoc/public_and_broadcasting.html#ADS</a>
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">BROADCASTING AND ADVERTISING </span>
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">Business Practices, Advertising Rates, and Profits.</span> Except with respect to political advertisements, we do not regulate a station's advertising rates or its profits. Rates charged for broadcast time are matters for negotiation between sponsors and stations. Further, except for certain classes of political advertisements (which we discuss elsewhere in this manual), stations are free to accept or reject any advertising.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I'm simply saying that if you as a business are going to treat one type of ad a certain way in regards to it's suitability, you have to treat them all with that standard. To do otherwise, ESPECIALLY if you're doing it as federally regulated media - is a despicable act.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
It would be more despicable to use the heavy hand of the government to deprive a private network of its freedom to choose what ads it can and cannot air.  Besides, NBC chose not to air an ad it found impuned other religions.  If a Coke or Burger King ad did the same thing, I would expect them to choose not to air the ad too.  It seems to me they are applying the same standard to thier advertizing in that regard.
<br />

<br />
At this point, it's pretty clear you're just crying because NBC chose to to air a message you really like.  Perhaps you would be happier in a country where the government more control over the media and less freedom of the press so that people can be forced to agree with you all the time..<br />_________________<br />Old Bard of Brell
<br />
Proud Member of Poison Arrow</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
